    {
        "content": "<p>I'm wondering how far we are from the following result: a Hahn series K[[T^Γ]] where K is real-closed and Γ is divisible is also real-closed. This result is relevant to me since it shows that surreal numbers (which are isomorphic to real Hahn series over themselves) are a real-closed field.</p>",
        "id": 506689132,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1742380250
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>cc <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"400289\">@Artie Khovanov</span> who has thought about that</p>",
        "id": 506690761,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1742380688
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I have proved a slightly weaker result - Puiseaux rather than Hahn series - in Isabelle by generalising the analogous proof over ACFs. The proof is fairly elementary, progressively generalising Hensel's Lemma for power series by coordinate transformations. This makes it attractive for formalisation.</p>\n<p>I have been working towards the theory of RCFs in Lean, but I haven't really done much since the Autumn. I wanted to do it properly, developing some real algebra etc first, but got a bit lost in scope creep (eg Mathlib is missing basic results on sums of squares).</p>\n<p>You don't really need any RCF / Artin-Schreier theory for your result, of course - as long as you choose the right definition of an RCF ;)<br>\nI'd be happy to provide you a sketch of my argument and my references -- as far as I know, the RCF version is not published anywhere. Probably you can mine my proof to get to whatever version you need.</p>",
        "id": 506693681,
        "sender_full_name": "Artie Khovanov",
        "timestamp": 1742381511
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What would the correct definition of an RCF be? In truth I don't think I'm looking for any particular definition of an RCF, since this result is likely to be a leaf result.</p>",
        "id": 506697841,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1742382670
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>References would be quite welcome, since I'm not very familiar with this part of algebra.</p>",
        "id": 506697981,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1742382715
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Here are 4 characterisations of an RCF:<br>\n(1) Ordered field in which every positive element has a square root and every odd-degree polynomial has a root<br>\n(2) Ordered field satisfying the Intermediate Value Property for polynomials<br>\n(3) Ordered field maximal among algebraic extensions of ordered fields<br>\n(4) Model of Th(\\bbR) in the language of ordered fields</p>\n<p>(1) is the most hands on for algebraic stuff, and the one you'll want, but quite artificial<br>\n(2) is the best for developing \"algebraic analysis\" but also a bit artificial<br>\n(3) is more conceptual, it's what I would say an RCF \"is\" but I'm not an expert<br>\n(4) is cool and really strong</p>\n<p>Proving equivalence of (1),(2),(3) is well within the scope of my Lean work; proving they imply (4) requires the Sturm-Tarski QE stuff and I think we are miles away from it.</p>",
        "id": 506700152,
        "sender_full_name": "Artie Khovanov",
        "timestamp": 1742383383
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Any of the first three would be pretty great.</p>",
        "id": 506701176,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1742383722
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>OK I found the result I generalised to, it's pretty cursed:<br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/24u4yLsvLFoLjvSuPOjuHxKc/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/24u4yLsvLFoLjvSuPOjuHxKc/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"654x410\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/3121/24u4yLsvLFoLjvSuPOjuHxKc/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div>",
        "id": 506702877,
        "sender_full_name": "Artie Khovanov",
        "timestamp": 1742384256
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This result is taken from mining the proof of the Newton-Puiseaux theorem given by Shreeram S. Abhyankar in <em>Algebraic Geometry for Scientists and Engineers</em> (pp. 92 - 94).<br>\nYou can actually read it on Google Books: <a href=\"https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=14LyBwAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PA92\">https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=14LyBwAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PA92</a></p>",
        "id": 506703205,
        "sender_full_name": "Artie Khovanov",
        "timestamp": 1742384361
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>With this result, let <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span> be an RCF -- characterisation (1). Then</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p>You can find a root of an odd-degree polynomial over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>K</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">⟨</mo><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">⟨</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">⟩</mo><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">⟩</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K\\langle\\!\\!\\!\\langle X\\rangle\\!\\!\\!\\rangle</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"mopen\">⟨</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">⟨</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">⟩</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mclose\">⟩</span></span></span></span> by applying the corollary by induction on degree.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>You can obtain a root of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>X</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>−</mo><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X^2-f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8974em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">−</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span>, where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f&gt;0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">&gt;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span>, by lifting a root of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>X</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>−</mo><mi>a</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X^2-a</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8974em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">−</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span></span></span></span>, where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">a&gt;0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">&gt;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span> is the leading coefficient of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span>, using part (2) of the theorem.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 506704717,
        "sender_full_name": "Artie Khovanov",
        "timestamp": 1742384777
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The source is the following slides:<br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/UfW3cYNOgBA1-J1g6QrKal47/cambridge_talk.pdf\">cambridge_talk.pdf</a><br>\nFrom the following talk:<br>\n<a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HBPg-K9ieng\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HBPg-K9ieng</a><br>\n(The talk isn't focused on the maths unfortunately)</p>\n<div class=\"youtube-video message_inline_image\"><a data-id=\"HBPg-K9ieng\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HBPg-K9ieng\"><img src=\"https://uploads.zulipusercontent.net/8dc231da3ffee8db8e78845e9392d94162317490/68747470733a2f2f692e7974696d672e636f6d2f76692f484250672d4b3969656e672f6d7164656661756c742e6a7067\"></a></div>",
